00:49:18.855 --> 00:49:19.980
AUDIENCE: Difficulty level?

00:49:19.980 --> 00:49:20.646
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:49:20.646 --> 00:49:21.922
Where is that?

00:49:21.922 --> 00:49:23.380
AUDIENCE: Your
difficulty function.

00:49:23.380 --> 00:49:24.424
PROFESSOR: Which is?

00:49:24.424 --> 00:49:25.090
AUDIENCE: Delta.

00:49:25.090 --> 00:49:27.350
PROFESSOR: Delta.

00:49:27.350 --> 00:49:27.850
So, yeah.

00:49:27.850 --> 00:49:29.710
The weight is delta.

00:49:29.710 --> 00:49:31.220
I drew d.

00:49:31.220 --> 00:49:36.880
Delta of these two
foot positions.

00:49:36.880 --> 00:49:37.660
Almost.

00:49:37.660 --> 00:49:42.260
If I want to minimize the
difficulty, then this is right.

00:49:42.260 --> 00:49:44.040
If I want to maximize
a score, then I

00:49:44.040 --> 00:49:47.404
would have to add a minus sign.

00:49:47.404 --> 00:49:49.070
But if you're minimizing
the difficulty,

00:49:49.070 --> 00:49:51.520
this is exactly the way because
it maps the shortest path.

00:49:51.520 --> 00:49:55.302
Usually, in dynamic programming,
things are maximized.

00:49:55.302 --> 00:49:57.586
AUDIENCE: Wait, why would
you add a minus if it's--

00:49:57.586 --> 00:49:59.460
PROFESSOR: So, if we're
maximizing something,

00:49:59.460 --> 00:50:02.165
we have to flip-- we have to
add a minus to the edge costs

00:50:02.165 --> 00:50:02.665
because--

00:50:02.665 --> 00:50:03.520
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:03.700
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:50:03.700 --> 00:50:05.590
But this time we're
minimizing something.

00:50:05.590 --> 00:50:05.802
AUDIENCE: Oh.

00:50:05.802 --> 00:50:06.580
Right, right, right.

00:50:06.580 --> 00:50:08.260
PROFESSOR: I promised you
